contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:10.681 --> 01:13.783
May I come in?

01:13.818 --> 01:16.086
[ALARM CLOCK BLARES]

01:16.120 --> 01:21.591
♪

01:21.625 --> 01:27.297
♪

01:27.331 --> 01:29.099
♪ I don't want much ♪

01:29.133 --> 01:31.434
♪ I just wanna be a better man ♪

01:31.469 --> 01:32.502
♪ To my baby ♪

01:32.536 --> 01:35.438
♪ Mm, mm ♪

01:35.473 --> 01:37.006
♪

01:37.041 --> 01:41.166
♪ What can I do? What can I do? ♪

01:41.201 --> 01:43.179
♪ To get back to your heart ♪

01:44.515 --> 01:47.183
♪ I'd swim the Mississippi river ♪

01:47.218 --> 01:50.520
♪ If you would give me
another start, girl ♪

01:50.554 --> 01:54.057
♪

01:54.091 --> 01:57.360
♪

01:57.394 --> 02:00.964
♪

02:00.998 --> 02:05.735
♪ What can I do? What can I do? ♪

02:05.769 --> 02:07.203
♪ To get back to your heart ♪

02:08.771 --> 02:11.407
♪ I'd swim the Mississippi river ♪

02:11.442 --> 02:16.411
♪ If you would give me
another start, girl ♪

02:16.446 --> 02:18.080
[HORNS HONK]

02:18.114 --> 02:20.516
Shade grown. Macadamia milk.

02:20.550 --> 02:22.484
[CLEARS THROAT] And still I'll drink it.

02:22.519 --> 02:24.753
- Why are you working out here?
- Mm.

02:24.787 --> 02:26.321
My office... there's stuff in it.

02:26.356 --> 02:28.044
You could move it.

02:28.078 --> 02:29.458
And I like looking up at that.

02:30.460 --> 02:32.161
- Duty.
- Duty.

02:32.195 --> 02:34.363
- Duty.
- This makes you happy?

02:34.397 --> 02:36.619
- A little bit.
- What do I do on duty?

02:36.620 --> 02:37.887
Mm, you have two choices.

02:37.922 --> 02:39.522
You can walk across Foley Square

02:39.557 --> 02:41.191
and tell Tina Krissman you're on duty,

02:41.225 --> 02:43.455
in which case, she'll give you this...

02:46.256 --> 02:47.595
Okay. I got it.

02:48.365 --> 02:49.886
Okay.

02:49.927 --> 02:51.728
...or you can check your e-mail.
Either way.

02:51.762 --> 02:53.563
Hey, what are you doing here?

02:53.597 --> 02:54.831
- I work here.
- Fraud.

02:54.865 --> 02:56.544
No, seriously.
I was sworn in with you guys.

02:56.545 --> 02:57.511
That's my office right there.

02:57.546 --> 02:58.846
I got a fraud case.

02:58.880 --> 02:59.980
You had a fraud case, right?

03:00.015 --> 03:01.248
Against Kate Littlejohn.

03:01.283 --> 03:02.750
Is your case against Kate Littlejohn?

03:02.784 --> 03:03.651
No.

03:03.685 --> 03:05.352
Then you should be fine.

03:05.387 --> 03:07.254
I meant, what are you
doing here so early?

03:07.289 --> 03:08.422
Drug hearing.

03:08.457 --> 03:09.690
And now I'm late.

03:09.724 --> 03:11.826
What kind of fraud?

03:11.860 --> 03:13.327
JUDGE VAUGHN: Wine?

03:13.361 --> 03:14.442
BROTI: Yes, Your Honor.

03:14.476 --> 03:17.498
The defendant, Mr. Mahler,
is a wine forger.

03:17.532 --> 03:18.933
As alleged the indictment,

03:18.967 --> 03:20.634
Mr. Mahler was filling bottles

03:20.669 --> 03:23.037
that appeared to be
rare and expensive vintages

03:23.071 --> 03:24.438
with cheap, fake wine.

03:24.473 --> 03:26.807
Basically fair, but I wouldn't
really call it "cheap".

03:26.842 --> 03:27.949
No talking.

03:27.983 --> 03:29.782
The indictment alleges he made millions.

03:29.816 --> 03:31.863
Those assets were frozen
by the government, Your Honor.

03:31.897 --> 03:34.148
Which is why he needs a public defender.

03:34.182 --> 03:36.050
- Yes, Your Honor.
- Thank you.

03:36.084 --> 03:37.518
With the standard restrictions

03:37.552 --> 03:39.120
and the added requirement

03:39.154 --> 03:40.888
that Mr. Mahler refrains from

03:40.922 --> 03:43.724
the manufacture, sale,
or consumption of wine,

03:43.758 --> 03:45.359
I'll release him pending trial.

03:45.393 --> 03:46.927
We'll stand in recess.

03:50.398 --> 03:52.500
I'd like for you to come by
my office this afternoon

03:52.534 --> 03:53.734
so we can discuss some things.

03:53.768 --> 03:55.536
- It's a date.
- It's not a date.

03:55.570 --> 03:56.826
I can bring lunch.

03:56.861 --> 03:58.038
Don't.

03:58.773 --> 03:59.974
[ELEVATOR DINGS]

04:05.496 --> 04:07.116
October 5th, 1998...

04:07.151 --> 04:08.415
you remember anything about it?

04:08.450 --> 04:09.550
I was in sixth grade.

04:09.584 --> 04:10.885
Phil Stoller's wedding day.

04:10.919 --> 04:13.254
Congressman Phil Stoller
from the New York 16th?

04:13.288 --> 04:14.522
From the front page.

04:14.556 --> 04:16.257
He's having an affair.

04:16.291 --> 04:18.425
Wasn't a great wedding. Bad oysters.

04:18.459 --> 04:22.428
An ice sculpture that melted
into the shape of a penis.

04:22.463 --> 04:24.598
First dance to "Mustang Sally".

04:24.633 --> 04:26.567
I knew the marriage
was never gonna work out.

04:26.601 --> 04:28.369
I didn't know it was gonna take me out.

04:28.403 --> 04:29.503
Out of what?

04:29.538 --> 04:32.239
The woman Congressman Stoller
was having an affair with

04:32.274 --> 04:33.607
was also married to a printer.

04:33.642 --> 04:36.110
Two days after he found out
about the affair,

04:36.144 --> 04:37.678
Stoller paid half a million dollars

04:37.712 --> 04:38.779
in federal campaign funds

04:38.813 --> 04:40.581
to the husband's printing business.

04:40.615 --> 04:42.550
Hush money, so he wouldn't
expose the affair.

04:42.584 --> 04:43.450
That's the question.

04:43.485 --> 04:45.186
If we can prove Stoller paid the money

04:45.220 --> 04:46.720
in order to keep the affair secret,

04:46.755 --> 04:47.922
we have a case against him

04:47.956 --> 04:49.890
for misappropriation of campaign funds.

04:49.925 --> 04:51.525
If we can't, then we don't.

04:51.560 --> 04:54.094
Roger's conflicted out
because he went to the wedding.

04:54.129 --> 04:55.529
I've already suffered terribly.

04:55.564 --> 04:57.198
That sculpture... it haunts me.

04:57.232 --> 04:59.066
So, this is yours, son.

04:59.100 --> 05:00.267
I honestly have no idea

05:00.302 --> 05:02.203
who you are or where you came from,

05:02.237 --> 05:04.205
but you have Roger's attention.

05:04.239 --> 05:06.574
Nail this case, and you'll have mine.

05:10.101 --> 05:11.879
What are you doing?

05:11.913 --> 05:12.813
Getting ahead of things.

05:12.847 --> 05:14.448
You're getting ahead of work
in my office?

05:14.482 --> 05:16.483
No, I'm getting ahead of
you coming to my office

05:16.518 --> 05:18.085
and interrupting <i>my</i> work.

05:18.119 --> 05:18.919
If I start in here,

05:18.954 --> 05:20.721
I figure I might be safe for the day.

05:20.755 --> 05:22.122
I'll probably still come by.

05:22.157 --> 05:23.624
I've got a big drug case.

05:23.658 --> 05:26.160
This guy gets paid $100
to deliver a package,

05:26.194 --> 05:27.661
throws it in his backpack,

05:27.696 --> 05:29.797
goes into the station at 116th Street,

05:29.831 --> 05:30.664
jumps a turnstile

05:30.699 --> 05:32.499
and gets stopped by a few beat cops.

05:32.534 --> 05:33.734
- Mm-hmm.
- That package?

05:33.768 --> 05:35.569
57 grams of meth.

05:35.604 --> 05:37.471
- 57 grams?
- That's right.

05:38.376 --> 05:41.175
This is 57 grams, and anything over 50

05:41.209 --> 05:43.611
is a mandatory minimum
of 10 years in prison.

05:43.645 --> 05:45.646
The only thing big about your case...

05:45.680 --> 05:47.281
is the sentence.

05:47.664 --> 05:49.316
Thanks for the visit.

05:51.238 --> 05:53.520
My cousin's friend had this friend.

05:53.555 --> 05:55.956
Heard I knew this other guy
from back in the day.

05:55.991 --> 05:57.157
Said I could make some money

05:57.192 --> 05:58.592
if I was willing to be a go-between.

05:58.627 --> 05:59.793
Had you done this before?

05:59.828 --> 06:01.962
- Maybe a few times.
- Mm.

06:01.997 --> 06:03.764
I'm a father now, you know?

06:03.798 --> 06:05.666
I'm just trying to provide.

06:05.700 --> 06:07.434
I didn't know what was in the backpack.

06:07.469 --> 06:09.136
- What did you think it was?
- I don't know.

06:09.170 --> 06:10.371
Something.

06:10.405 --> 06:11.705
I didn't ask.

06:11.740 --> 06:14.074
But I didn't know.

06:16.144 --> 06:18.312
You think there's maybe
a way out of this?

06:19.547 --> 06:21.248
I'll do everything I can.

06:23.551 --> 06:25.519
I completely disagree.

06:25.553 --> 06:27.121
Did you read the paper today?

06:27.155 --> 06:28.255
I don't read the paper.

06:28.290 --> 06:31.422
This kid, Julien Barley,
got stomped to death in prison.

06:31.456 --> 06:32.860
Prison's a tough place.

06:32.894 --> 06:34.461
He didn't belong there.

06:35.363 --> 06:36.530
A lot of people don't.

06:36.564 --> 06:38.017
He lived next door to a stash house.

06:38.051 --> 06:41.468
He went over to play video games
with one of his friends

06:41.503 --> 06:42.870
and the cops raided the place.

06:42.904 --> 06:45.306
There were 12 kilos of cocaine

06:45.340 --> 06:47.841
hidden away in the house.

06:47.876 --> 06:49.576
And Julien?

06:49.611 --> 06:52.413
Got 10 years for playing video games.

06:52.447 --> 06:54.348
This is why I don't read the paper.

06:54.382 --> 06:55.983
Why are you making me wait?

06:57.218 --> 06:58.385
Right.

07:05.311 --> 07:06.694
Just another day, Judge.

07:07.796 --> 07:14.201
♪

07:14.235 --> 07:20.674
♪

07:20.709 --> 07:22.109
MAN: All rise.

07:22.143 --> 07:29.550
♪

07:29.584 --> 07:31.785
- Mr. Oliver?
- SETH: Thank you, Your Honor.

07:31.820 --> 07:34.054
Rodrigo Puente is charged
in Count 1 of the indictment

07:34.089 --> 07:35.923
with the possession of
a controlled substance

07:35.957 --> 07:37.558
with an intent to distribute.

07:37.592 --> 07:38.592
What substance?

07:38.626 --> 07:39.526
Methamphetamine.

07:39.561 --> 07:41.362
Mr, Puente, have you had an opportunity

07:41.396 --> 07:42.396
to read the indictment?

07:42.430 --> 07:43.430
Yes, Your Honor.

07:43.465 --> 07:45.299
And do you understand the nature
of the charges against you?

07:45.333 --> 07:46.300
Yes, Your Honor.

07:47.063 --> 07:48.802
Was Mr. Puente selling?

07:48.837 --> 07:50.270
No, Your Honor.

07:52.273 --> 07:54.174
- He was a courier?
- Yes, Your Honor.

07:55.677 --> 07:56.744
How much meth?

07:56.778 --> 07:58.145
57 grams.

07:58.179 --> 07:59.913
57 grams?

08:00.588 --> 08:03.217
This is a mandatory minimum of 10 years.

08:03.251 --> 08:04.818
SETH: Yes, Your Honor.

08:05.468 --> 08:06.963
Any criminal history?

08:06.998 --> 08:08.522
- Two prior convictions.
- For?

08:08.556 --> 08:11.625
Shoplifting and driving
with a suspended license.

08:12.350 --> 08:14.428
- Misdemeanors.
- Yes, Your Honor.

08:14.462 --> 08:15.362
Non-violent offenses

08:15.397 --> 08:17.164
for which Mr. Puente served no jail time.

08:17.198 --> 08:19.133
And yet still,
two criminal history points

08:19.167 --> 08:20.234
under the statute,

08:20.268 --> 08:23.170
which means he's ineligible
for the safety valve.

08:23.204 --> 08:24.605
SETH: Yes, Your Honor.

08:29.778 --> 08:31.945
In terms of a trial date, we propose...

08:31.980 --> 08:34.081
I don't like this case, Mr. Oliver.

08:34.581 --> 08:35.982
I'm sorry, Your Honor?

08:36.017 --> 08:38.083
I don't like this case.

08:39.020 --> 08:40.854
If Mr. Puente is convicted,

08:40.889 --> 08:42.356
I'll be forced to impose a sentence

08:42.390 --> 08:44.091
of 10 years in federal prison

08:44.125 --> 08:45.926
with no chance of parole

08:45.960 --> 08:48.796
on someone with essentially
no criminal history

08:48.830 --> 08:50.864
for carrying a package of meth

08:50.899 --> 08:52.666
the size of your phone.

08:52.700 --> 08:54.802
This is the same mandatory minimum

08:54.836 --> 08:58.005
Mr. Puente would face
for sex trafficking a child.

08:58.039 --> 09:00.774
I am not going to sentence Mr. Puente

09:00.809 --> 09:02.810
to 10 years in prison.

09:03.811 --> 09:05.946
Not today.

09:05.980 --> 09:12.943
Synced & corrected by -robtor-
www.addic7ed.com

09:13.675 --> 09:15.142
The judge wants us to take another look

09:15.177 --> 09:17.173
- at the Puente prosecution.
- Done.

09:17.207 --> 09:18.816
He's unhappy with the charges.

09:18.841 --> 09:20.033
He's unhappy with the law.

09:20.068 --> 09:21.376
Tell him to write his Congressman.

09:21.410 --> 09:22.877
Do you actually want me to tell him that?

09:22.911 --> 09:25.046
Or you can tell him
to rev up the DeLorean

09:25.080 --> 09:26.681
and take Mr. Puente back in time

09:26.715 --> 09:29.240
to before he decided to carry
57 grams of meth.

09:29.275 --> 09:31.425
I'll probably just tell the
judge our position stands,

09:31.460 --> 09:33.020
- leave out the rest.
- Either way.

09:33.055 --> 09:34.233
Who's the judge?

09:34.267 --> 09:35.467
Byrne.

09:35.501 --> 09:37.041
JILL: Doesn't sound like Judge Byrne.

09:37.075 --> 09:38.092
Is this unusual?

09:38.127 --> 09:41.496
Judges will sometimes express their
displeasure about something.

09:41.530 --> 09:43.364
I've never heard of something so direct.

09:43.399 --> 09:44.465
It was pretty direct.

09:45.326 --> 09:46.393
Who is that?

09:48.883 --> 09:49.916
No idea.

09:51.192 --> 09:52.726
That's her duty case?

09:54.276 --> 09:55.676
Really?

09:56.754 --> 09:57.845
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

09:57.880 --> 10:00.047
Roger and Delap just gave me
a new investigation.

10:00.082 --> 10:02.374
I'm incredibly happy for you.

10:02.409 --> 10:03.508
Really?

10:03.543 --> 10:05.054
No. I don't care.

10:05.088 --> 10:07.789
It's a sensitive case, so I
can't get into the details...

10:07.823 --> 10:08.923
Perfect.

10:08.957 --> 10:11.692
If I can make this, I think I'll
really be on Delap's radar.

10:14.919 --> 10:15.919
You okay?

10:15.953 --> 10:17.254
I'm fine.

10:17.288 --> 10:18.822
Yeah?

10:18.856 --> 10:20.690
Yeah.

10:22.460 --> 10:25.171
I'm going to donor lunch
tomorrow with my mom.

10:25.172 --> 10:27.473
She always likes it when I show my
face, do a little "grip-and-grin".

10:27.507 --> 10:28.841
If you're interested.

10:28.875 --> 10:31.281
I don't grip, I don't grin.
Zero interest.

10:31.845 --> 10:33.312
Yeah, you seem fine.

10:37.184 --> 10:39.006
- TOBY: Thanks for having me in.
- I'm your lawyer.

10:39.040 --> 10:40.086
Still.

10:40.120 --> 10:42.154
These are serious charges, Toby.

10:42.189 --> 10:44.056
Well, then, I'm glad
I have a serious lawyer.

10:44.091 --> 10:45.291
Too serious, maybe?

10:46.927 --> 10:48.060
What is that?

10:48.095 --> 10:49.395
The judge specifically said

10:49.429 --> 10:51.564
no manufacturing, sale, or consumption.

10:51.598 --> 10:53.099
This is a gift.

10:53.133 --> 10:55.267
Have you ever had
a 1982 Chateau Blanquefort?

10:55.302 --> 10:57.436
- It's evidence.
- Of God.

10:57.471 --> 10:58.871
It's transcendent.

10:58.905 --> 11:00.172
Lush and supple.

11:00.207 --> 11:02.538
Velvet on the tongue, visceral.

11:02.573 --> 11:05.344
Like nothing you've ever
experienced in your life.

11:06.880 --> 11:08.414
The real stuff, anyway.

11:08.448 --> 11:11.617
This... is a fake. Here, have it.

11:11.651 --> 11:13.629
You'll never be able
to tell the difference.

11:13.663 --> 11:15.354
I can tell the difference.

11:15.388 --> 11:17.423
You can't. Most people can't.

11:17.457 --> 11:19.725
Most people have no idea
what they're drinking.

11:19.760 --> 11:22.027
If the label is attractive
and the price is high,

11:22.062 --> 11:23.095
it's good.

11:23.130 --> 11:25.397
If it's cheap and unattractive,

11:25.432 --> 11:26.432
it's not good.

11:26.466 --> 11:27.767
You went to Yale, right?

11:27.801 --> 11:29.969
- Yes.
- Same thing.

11:30.003 --> 11:31.403
I hear "Yale",

11:31.438 --> 11:32.972
I think "you're a great lawyer."

11:33.006 --> 11:34.740
I don't hear "Yale", then I wonder...

11:34.775 --> 11:35.741
what are you?

11:35.776 --> 11:37.409
I'm a great lawyer.

11:37.444 --> 11:38.744
Ah, I hope so.

11:39.224 --> 11:42.151
The point is, I love wine.

11:42.186 --> 11:44.483
I dropped out of community
college when I was 19.

11:44.518 --> 11:45.751
I worked for a year

11:45.786 --> 11:47.553
to save up money to go to France,

11:47.587 --> 11:49.789
and the day I had my first real Burgundy,

11:49.823 --> 11:51.891
I knew.

11:51.925 --> 11:53.492
This is what I was meant to do.

11:53.527 --> 11:55.327
I loved everything about it...

11:55.362 --> 11:57.329
the craft, the history.

11:57.364 --> 11:59.231
Started collecting.

11:59.266 --> 12:00.766
I was happy.

12:00.801 --> 12:04.403
And then one day, I accidentally
bought a fake bottle.

12:04.437 --> 12:06.238
It actually broke my heart.

12:06.273 --> 12:08.318
I started to see it all around me.

12:08.352 --> 12:09.542
The posers,

12:09.576 --> 12:11.577
people pretending to care about wine

12:11.611 --> 12:14.580
when all they cared about
was the money, the status.

12:14.614 --> 12:16.916
Forgery was my revenge.

12:16.950 --> 12:19.351
You know, if I hadn't slipped up

12:19.386 --> 12:21.086
and made these little typos,

12:21.121 --> 12:22.521
nobody ever would have known.

12:22.556 --> 12:25.124
♪

12:25.158 --> 12:27.927
Your watch... it's a fake.

12:27.961 --> 12:31.330
This was a gift from my parents.

12:31.364 --> 12:32.765
♪

12:32.799 --> 12:34.466
It's the thought that counts.

12:34.501 --> 12:36.228
♪

12:36.263 --> 12:38.370
People need to know the truth
about Congressman Stoller.

12:38.405 --> 12:41.440
SARAH: The truth is, I wanted to
leave my husband and marry Phil.

12:41.474 --> 12:44.677
He begged me to wait
until after his reelection.

12:44.711 --> 12:47.446
He told me he would leave his wife, too.

12:47.480 --> 12:48.848
That was four years ago.

12:48.882 --> 12:50.616
I let him string me along

12:50.650 --> 12:53.052
until he and my husband
settled on a price.

12:53.086 --> 12:55.454
Now I'm stuck in this hotel room.

12:55.488 --> 12:56.822
No home to go back to.

12:56.857 --> 12:59.458
I can't go outside without
the tabloids chasing me.

13:00.346 --> 13:03.128
Your husband found out about the
affair on the morning of the 14th?

13:03.163 --> 13:04.204
Yes.

13:04.238 --> 13:07.366
And he confronted Stoller on the 15th.

13:07.400 --> 13:08.667
Two days later on the 17th,

13:08.702 --> 13:10.052
your husband's printing company

13:10.086 --> 13:12.504
got a huge order
from the Stoller campaign...

13:12.539 --> 13:14.173
half a million dollars.

13:14.207 --> 13:16.976
Phil paid him off
to keep the affair quiet.

13:17.010 --> 13:18.744
That's certainly what it looks like,

13:18.778 --> 13:19.979
but it's circumstantial.

13:20.013 --> 13:22.147
Except it's not. He told me.

13:22.182 --> 13:24.717
My husband said he was gonna
make Phil pay.

13:24.751 --> 13:26.801
- He said that?
- More than once.

13:26.836 --> 13:29.054
And Phil called me and said
he was gonna pay.

13:29.089 --> 13:30.422
Do you have any e-mails or texts

13:30.457 --> 13:33.058
or any written communication
about any of this?

13:33.093 --> 13:34.126
No.

13:35.528 --> 13:37.162
But you have me.

13:37.197 --> 13:39.352
♪

13:39.386 --> 13:40.432
Mr. Oliver.

13:40.467 --> 13:43.502
Has the government had an opportunity
to reconsider its position?

13:43.536 --> 13:44.737
SETH: Yes, Your Honor.

13:44.771 --> 13:46.872
The government's position is unchanged.

13:47.769 --> 13:50.336
Tell Roger Gunn I want to
see him in my chambers.

13:50.371 --> 13:51.644
I've spoken to Mr. Gunn

13:51.678 --> 13:54.380
and advised him of
the circumstances, Your Honor.

13:54.414 --> 13:55.681
I'm here.

13:55.715 --> 13:58.450
I represent the United States Government.

13:58.485 --> 14:00.619
Mr. Oliver.

14:00.654 --> 14:02.554
Please approach.

14:10.463 --> 14:12.965
Did you represent
the United States Government

14:12.999 --> 14:14.400
in the Locarno matter

14:14.434 --> 14:17.436
when you added charges
to the superseding indictment

14:17.470 --> 14:19.605
for the sole purpose of
pressuring Ms. Locarno

14:19.639 --> 14:20.639
into a plea deal

14:20.674 --> 14:24.510
in violation of the
US Attorney Manual 9-27.300?

14:26.313 --> 14:27.915
I want to talk about Rodrigo Puente.

14:27.950 --> 14:30.115
- I know why we're here.
- He's facing 10 years.

14:30.150 --> 14:31.550
I didn't write the law.

14:31.584 --> 14:33.519
- If he had seven grams less...
- He didn't.

14:35.755 --> 14:37.735
I'm just trying to talk with you.

14:39.092 --> 14:40.592
That's what this is, a talk?

14:40.627 --> 14:42.970
Without defense counsel,
without a court reporter?

14:43.616 --> 14:45.597
I don't like this kind of talk.

14:46.607 --> 14:48.113
What are you doing, Judge?

14:48.548 --> 14:50.688
I'm trying to do the right thing.

14:52.872 --> 14:54.640
"I don't care about what you believe.

14:54.674 --> 14:56.342
Win the damn case!"

14:56.376 --> 14:58.911
That's what you taught me
when you had my job

14:58.945 --> 15:00.312
and I was Seth Oliver.

15:00.347 --> 15:01.676
I was wrong.

15:01.710 --> 15:03.928
No, you were right.

15:04.517 --> 15:05.617
You were tough.

15:05.652 --> 15:07.686
You believed that if we got
emotional about every case,

15:07.721 --> 15:09.980
we couldn't do our job
and that our job is important.

15:10.015 --> 15:11.623
You said drugs had victims

15:11.658 --> 15:14.059
and we cared about those victims.

15:15.528 --> 15:17.096
You were right.

15:17.130 --> 15:18.764
♪

15:18.798 --> 15:21.533
I'm not letting this go.

15:22.447 --> 15:24.169
Then Rodrigo Puente

15:24.204 --> 15:26.429
isn't the only person
who's gonna suffer here.

15:26.464 --> 15:33.112
♪

15:34.579 --> 15:39.227
MELORA: [CHUCKLES] Well, that's
a hell of a question, Steve,

15:39.252 --> 15:42.154
how the Senate will handle
banking reform.

15:42.189 --> 15:44.356
And you want me to answer that

15:44.391 --> 15:47.393
with all these bankers
standing 10 feet away?

15:47.427 --> 15:48.861
[LAUGHTER] Thanks a lot!

15:48.895 --> 15:50.763
♪

15:50.797 --> 15:52.998
Fortunately, I get to change the subject

15:53.033 --> 15:55.167
and introduce my eldest son, Leonard,

15:55.202 --> 15:57.523
who thinks I didn't see him slip in.

15:58.205 --> 15:59.538
MELORA: Jim Orsua at Hartmann-Carlyle?

15:59.573 --> 16:00.506
- Yes.
- You talked to him?

16:00.540 --> 16:01.607
Yes. He introduced himself.

16:01.641 --> 16:03.409
He went to Harvard, too.

16:03.443 --> 16:05.377
So did everyone in that room.

16:05.412 --> 16:07.112
Charlie Phillips at Rincon.

16:07.147 --> 16:09.415
Darren Caner from Rock River Equity.

16:09.449 --> 16:10.716
Steve Hewes at Vonner Capital.

16:10.750 --> 16:12.480
They've all been good supporters.

16:12.515 --> 16:13.886
I talked to them all.

16:13.920 --> 16:15.387
I need to get back.

16:15.422 --> 16:18.224
To your investigation
of Congressman Stoller?

16:19.503 --> 16:21.260
When were you gonna tell me?

16:22.131 --> 16:25.007
You're interviewing his campaign staff.

16:25.032 --> 16:26.238
It's all over Washington.

16:26.272 --> 16:28.748
I don't have ravens watching you.

16:28.749 --> 16:30.216
I can't talk about Congressman Stoller.

16:30.250 --> 16:31.851
I don't want to talk
about the Congressman.

16:31.885 --> 16:33.653
I want to talk about you.

16:33.687 --> 16:36.222
This isn't good for you.

16:36.256 --> 16:38.057
It could be. If I win.

16:38.091 --> 16:39.225
And if you don't?

16:39.259 --> 16:40.775
When was the last time I didn't win?

16:40.809 --> 16:41.994
When you were a 1L.

16:42.029 --> 16:43.462
I won the Hotchkiss prize.

16:43.497 --> 16:45.031
Second semester, not the first.

16:45.065 --> 16:46.818
I don't care about Stoller.

16:46.853 --> 16:50.903
And I would never interfere
with a federal investigation.

16:50.938 --> 16:54.740
All I'm saying
is that you need to be careful.

16:54.775 --> 16:56.742
And I'm saying this as your mom.

16:56.777 --> 16:58.144
I know you are.

16:58.178 --> 17:00.346
And I appreciate it.

17:00.380 --> 17:01.714
But I got this.

17:01.748 --> 17:10.446
[SOFT PIANO MUSIC PLAYS]

17:10.481 --> 17:12.825
- Just the two of us?
- JUDGE BYRNE: Yes.

17:12.858 --> 17:14.359
Are you sure?

17:14.394 --> 17:15.994
Yes.

17:19.041 --> 17:21.477
Puente needs to trade up.

17:21.512 --> 17:22.744
If he can give
the government something...

17:22.780 --> 17:24.646
You don't think I know this? I know this.

17:24.681 --> 17:26.348
This is what I do.

17:26.383 --> 17:29.218
This is what I did with you many times.

17:29.253 --> 17:31.687
He doesn't have anything to trade, Judge.

17:31.722 --> 17:33.356
He has to find someone.

17:33.390 --> 17:36.058
Well, he can't make someone up.

17:36.093 --> 17:38.327
He doesn't deserve this.

17:39.083 --> 17:41.731
Neither did Jordan Ahmed.

17:41.765 --> 17:43.432
Or Michael Frontiere.

17:43.467 --> 17:45.935
Or Merced Jimenez,
and that was just last week.

17:45.969 --> 17:49.038
We defend people like
Rodrigo Puente every day,

17:49.072 --> 17:52.542
and every day, they don't deserve this.

17:53.431 --> 17:55.511
Today is different.

17:55.546 --> 17:57.180
The only thing
different about today is you.

17:57.214 --> 17:58.214
[SCOFFS]

17:58.248 --> 17:59.949
You've imposed this sentence

17:59.983 --> 18:02.785
more times than I can remember.

18:02.820 --> 18:06.088
When you went to the bench,
I wasn't optimistic.

18:06.123 --> 18:08.524
I'm speaking frankly, just the two of us.

18:08.559 --> 18:11.894
But you've surprised me...
your compassion, your mercy.

18:11.929 --> 18:15.077
You've also had blind spots,

18:15.966 --> 18:17.700
and this was one of them.

18:17.734 --> 18:23.973
♪

18:24.007 --> 18:26.422
This is a good thing,

18:27.110 --> 18:28.945
whatever's happening to you.

18:28.979 --> 18:35.651
♪

18:35.686 --> 18:41.622
♪

18:41.656 --> 18:44.260
SANDRA: "Stainless steel",
blah, blah, blah.

18:44.294 --> 18:45.628
Something about Geneva.

18:45.662 --> 18:47.296
Okay, here it is...

18:47.331 --> 18:48.831
each watch has a unique serial number

18:48.866 --> 18:49.899
engraved on the back.

18:49.933 --> 18:52.031
"H" followed by six numbers.

18:52.836 --> 18:55.004
Toby's right. It's a fake.

18:55.038 --> 18:56.138
Mm.

18:56.173 --> 18:58.074
Do you have any idea how much
my parents paid for this?

18:58.108 --> 18:59.742
Don't think about it.

18:59.776 --> 19:01.944
- Have more fake wine.
- [SIGHS]

19:03.280 --> 19:04.547
- Mmm. Ah!

19:05.782 --> 19:07.650
I really can't tell the difference.

19:07.684 --> 19:09.652
This guy is good.

19:09.686 --> 19:11.754
- Looking.
- That too.

19:11.788 --> 19:13.823
How is it that your first time on duty,

19:13.857 --> 19:15.364
you get him?

19:15.399 --> 19:17.340
Great packaging, I confess,

19:17.375 --> 19:20.296
but this is a hard case inside.

19:20.330 --> 19:22.164
He made fake wine. They found a lab.

19:22.199 --> 19:24.300
None of this is really in question.

19:24.334 --> 19:26.026
I should probably get rid of this, huh?

19:26.060 --> 19:28.337
Why? Because it doesn't have
an authentic serial number?

19:28.372 --> 19:29.372
Who cares?

19:29.406 --> 19:30.873
You love that watch.

19:30.908 --> 19:32.875
And it works.

19:32.910 --> 19:34.113
Does it work?

19:34.147 --> 19:35.978
Or do you think
that's why you get in late?

19:36.313 --> 19:37.947
It bothers me it isn't real.

19:37.981 --> 19:40.883
Are we really just going to
give up on that idea?

19:40.918 --> 19:42.852
That there is something important

19:42.886 --> 19:45.054
about quality and authenticity?

19:45.088 --> 19:46.722
Am I really supposed to believe

19:46.757 --> 19:48.624
that what's on the inside doesn't count?

19:49.326 --> 19:50.493
Toby believes that.

19:50.527 --> 19:52.028
He didn't always.

19:53.897 --> 19:56.065
He didn't always believe that.

19:56.099 --> 19:57.388
That's it.

19:58.869 --> 20:05.675
♪

20:05.709 --> 20:12.548
♪

20:12.582 --> 20:14.917
[KEYBOARD CLACKING]

20:14.952 --> 20:20.823
♪

20:20.857 --> 20:26.662
♪

20:26.697 --> 20:28.597
LEONARD: Let's talk about Vonner Capital.

20:28.632 --> 20:30.066
You know I have a tight schedule.

20:30.100 --> 20:30.967
What's this all about?

20:31.001 --> 20:32.535
Vonner Capital's where Phil Stoller went

20:32.569 --> 20:34.403
for the money to pay off
his mistress' husband.

20:34.438 --> 20:36.038
The top three executives
of Vonner Capital

20:36.073 --> 20:38.074
are all huge donors of yours, too.

20:38.108 --> 20:40.009
- I wasn't aware of that.
- I think you were.

20:40.043 --> 20:42.011
I think that's why
you wanted me off this case.

20:42.045 --> 20:43.879
If Vonner Capital gets implicated

20:43.914 --> 20:45.678
in a federal criminal investigation,

20:45.713 --> 20:47.144
you're linked to tainted donors,

20:47.179 --> 20:48.918
forced to return millions
in contributions.

20:48.952 --> 20:50.830
Your own fundraising
goes under the microscope.

20:50.864 --> 20:53.122
If I was so worried this
investigation would tarnish me,

20:53.156 --> 20:55.024
don't you think I'd ask you to drop it

20:55.058 --> 20:57.193
- instead of dropping <i>off</i> of it?
- You're too smart.

20:57.227 --> 20:58.761
That'd be obstruction.

20:58.795 --> 21:01.060
My career does not depend on one donor.

21:01.094 --> 21:04.600
Your career depends on
putting yourself first.

21:04.634 --> 21:06.002
Ahead of your own son.

21:08.071 --> 21:09.939
How can you even think that?

21:11.274 --> 21:12.775
First campaign you ever ran,

21:12.809 --> 21:13.976
how many TV ads did you stick me in?

21:14.011 --> 21:15.444
Four?

21:15.479 --> 21:16.812
I was a prop to you.

21:16.847 --> 21:17.980
I still am.

21:18.015 --> 21:19.148
You begged to be in those ads.

21:19.182 --> 21:20.549
I was 10,

21:20.584 --> 21:23.552
and maybe I just wanted
to be with my mom.

21:23.587 --> 21:25.554
It's not my career, Leonard. It's ours.

21:25.589 --> 21:28.124
In fact, yours more than mine.

21:28.158 --> 21:30.292
And you're gonna go
a lot farther than I have.

21:30.327 --> 21:32.316
You're gonna go all the way.

21:35.079 --> 21:37.733
JAY: If we can give the government
someone higher up... anyone...

21:37.768 --> 21:39.101
it might help.

21:39.136 --> 21:40.269
I don't know anybody.

21:40.303 --> 21:42.171
The person you got the package from.

21:42.205 --> 21:43.472
A.P.

21:43.507 --> 21:44.606
A.P.?

21:44.641 --> 21:46.842
He made less on this than I did.

21:46.877 --> 21:47.977
Is there anybody else?

21:48.011 --> 21:49.478
I'm not in the game.

21:49.513 --> 21:52.615
It was just... easy money.

21:53.337 --> 21:56.252
This judge, he's all right, right?

21:58.021 --> 21:59.822
He doesn't want
to sentence you to 10 years,

21:59.856 --> 22:01.424
- but if you don't...
- [SCOFFS] 10 years.

22:01.458 --> 22:03.359
10 years?

22:03.393 --> 22:07.763
♪

22:07.798 --> 22:12.001
My son, he's six months old.

22:12.035 --> 22:13.803
He's doing that thing where he...

22:13.837 --> 22:15.137
he pulls himself up.

22:15.172 --> 22:17.339
He's so proud, he's standing,

22:17.374 --> 22:21.177
and then boom, he's flat, you know?

22:21.211 --> 22:24.313
♪

22:24.347 --> 22:27.249
Like where the hell did
that floor come from?

22:33.157 --> 22:35.291
SETH: How long have you been
with the DEA, Agent Manello?

22:35.325 --> 22:36.619
11 years, 10 months.

22:36.654 --> 22:38.894
Based on your training
and experience, Agent Manello,

22:38.929 --> 22:39.962
do you have an opinion

22:39.996 --> 22:42.698
as to whether drug organizations
ever use couriers

22:42.732 --> 22:44.700
who are unaware of what
they're transporting?

22:44.734 --> 22:46.251
I've never seen that, sir.

22:46.285 --> 22:47.870
Agent Manello, you weren't
the arresting agent

22:47.904 --> 22:49.805
- in this case, correct?
- That's correct.

22:49.840 --> 22:51.874
And you have no previous history
with Mr. Puente?

22:51.908 --> 22:53.075
Correct.

22:53.110 --> 22:55.464
So is it fair to say that you
have no personal knowledge

22:55.498 --> 22:58.047
as to whether Mr. Puente was aware

22:58.081 --> 23:01.083
that the package he was carrying
contained methamphetamines?

23:01.118 --> 23:03.052
I can only testify to my experience.

23:03.086 --> 23:04.053
And in my experience,

23:04.087 --> 23:06.188
drug couriers always know
what they are carrying

23:06.223 --> 23:08.257
and when detained, always claim not to.

23:08.871 --> 23:11.160
But isn't it possible
that Mr. Puente thought...

23:11.194 --> 23:12.728
You ever order take-out?

23:13.730 --> 23:15.097
Yes, Your Honor.

23:15.132 --> 23:16.365
Ever pick up at the restaurant?

23:16.399 --> 23:17.399
Bag is stapled.

23:17.434 --> 23:19.301
You grab it, walk away,
don't look in the bag.

23:20.865 --> 23:22.138
I suppose I have, Your Honor.

23:22.172 --> 23:24.673
Now let's say you get stopped
on your walk home.

23:24.708 --> 23:26.036
Police look in the bag.

23:26.071 --> 23:28.110
Find out every carton in your take-out

23:28.145 --> 23:29.445
is packed with cocaine.

23:29.479 --> 23:30.880
What would you say?

23:30.914 --> 23:32.214
♪

23:32.249 --> 23:33.521
I asked you a question.

23:33.555 --> 23:35.417
I would say I didn't know
that was in there.

23:35.452 --> 23:37.019
So you'd agree it's at least possible

23:37.053 --> 23:38.237
Mr. Puente was carrying something

23:38.271 --> 23:39.889
he didn't know the contents of, right?

23:40.615 --> 23:41.795
I can't say.

23:41.829 --> 23:44.026
Well, you've done that. You just
testified you've done that, right?

23:44.060 --> 23:44.827
♪

23:44.861 --> 23:46.228
Answer the question, Agent Manello.

23:46.263 --> 23:47.796
Objection.

23:48.660 --> 23:50.199
Yes or no.

23:50.233 --> 23:51.248
Objection.

23:51.283 --> 23:53.481
I'm entitled to ask questions
in my own courtroom.

23:53.516 --> 23:55.137
And I'm entitled to object.

23:55.172 --> 23:56.372
This isn't gonna work.

23:56.406 --> 23:58.073
What you're doing...
it's never gonna work.

24:01.311 --> 24:02.278
You're right.

24:02.312 --> 24:03.397
It's not.

24:04.214 --> 24:07.550
I'm gonna instruct the jury
that if they convict Puente,

24:07.584 --> 24:08.951
he faces a mandatory minimum

24:08.985 --> 24:10.581
- of 10 years in prison.
- Judge...

24:10.615 --> 24:12.655
You cannot tell the jury
about the potential sentence.

24:12.689 --> 24:13.656
You cannot do that!

24:13.690 --> 24:15.224
I can, and I'm going to.

24:15.258 --> 24:18.327
That is a flagrant violation
of judicial conduct.

24:18.361 --> 24:21.497
Jill, this is wrong.

24:21.531 --> 24:25.167
♪

24:25.202 --> 24:26.602
I have a client.

24:26.636 --> 24:28.237
I work for Rodrigo Puente.

24:28.271 --> 24:31.273
♪

24:31.308 --> 24:33.509
I'm going to instruct the jury
about the sentence.

24:34.206 --> 24:38.948
I'm not sentencing Mr. Puente
to 10 years in prison.

24:38.982 --> 24:42.685
♪

24:44.714 --> 24:46.460
Forget your past with him for a second.

24:46.485 --> 24:48.420
- This isn't about my past with him.
- He's a good judge.

24:48.454 --> 24:50.699
I don't agree with him a lot. I don't.
But he's honorable.

24:50.733 --> 24:53.012
If he's willing to try something
this extreme,

24:53.037 --> 24:54.236
don't you think there
might be something here

24:54.270 --> 24:55.203
worth taking a minute to...

24:55.238 --> 24:57.572
There is nothing I can do.

24:57.607 --> 24:59.574
You could drop the quantity of drugs

24:59.609 --> 25:01.209
from the indictment.

25:01.244 --> 25:03.679
That gets him out from
the mandatory minimum.

25:03.713 --> 25:05.580
I don't want to get him out
from the mandatory minimum.

25:05.615 --> 25:06.949
You're working from the wrong assumption.

25:06.983 --> 25:08.102
This is the law.

25:08.136 --> 25:09.685
I'm trying to enforce the law.

25:14.290 --> 25:16.591
The Congressman places a massive order

25:16.626 --> 25:17.793
with a small, unproven,

25:17.827 --> 25:19.795
never-used-before printing company

25:19.829 --> 25:22.764
owned by the husband of
the Congressman's mistress.

25:22.799 --> 25:24.366
Bring charges.

25:24.400 --> 25:25.467
♪

25:25.501 --> 25:28.136
Congressman places a substantial
but much-needed order

25:28.171 --> 25:29.705
with a legitimate printing company

25:29.739 --> 25:30.906
in the last days of an expensive

25:30.940 --> 25:32.641
and competitive reelection campaign.

25:32.675 --> 25:34.576
Don't bring charges.

25:34.610 --> 25:36.111
The case relies entirely on the testimony

25:36.145 --> 25:37.646
of a credible, sympathetic witness

25:37.680 --> 25:38.547
with a consistent story

25:38.581 --> 25:41.249
and nothing to materially gain by lying.

25:41.284 --> 25:42.751
Bring charges.

25:42.785 --> 25:43.919
A case that relies entirely

25:43.953 --> 25:45.420
on the uncorroborated testimony

25:45.455 --> 25:46.822
of a self-righteously angry witness

25:46.856 --> 25:48.483
with a thirst for revenge.

25:48.518 --> 25:50.592
- Don't bring charges.
- [SIGHS]

25:51.861 --> 25:53.428
What's the score so far?

25:53.463 --> 25:55.130
It's a three-way tie
between "bring charges,"

25:55.164 --> 25:57.332
"don't bring charges,"
and "I shoot myself."

25:57.367 --> 25:59.466
- Do you want to know what my gut says?
- No.

25:59.500 --> 26:01.051
My gut says this a rare opportunity

26:01.086 --> 26:03.171
to make a personal impression
on the United States Attorney

26:03.206 --> 26:05.307
and the chance of that
happening again anytime soon

26:05.341 --> 26:06.575
is slim to nada.

26:06.609 --> 26:07.609
Don't do that.

26:07.643 --> 26:09.277
Mix English and Spanish
in the same sentence.

26:09.312 --> 26:10.312
- It's...
- Awesome?

26:10.346 --> 26:12.848
Terrible. Look, there is evidence

26:12.882 --> 26:14.483
and strong arguments on both sides.

26:14.517 --> 26:15.851
There's no right answer here.

26:15.885 --> 26:17.452
You just have to make a call.

26:17.487 --> 26:19.019
Can you grab me that binder?

26:27.389 --> 26:29.765
You gave up on what you cared about.

26:29.799 --> 26:31.666
You love wine,

26:31.701 --> 26:32.968
but you're helping to destroy it

26:33.002 --> 26:34.336
in the name of revenge.

26:34.370 --> 26:36.004
Don't do that.

26:36.039 --> 26:38.273
If there is rampant fraud
in the industry,

26:38.307 --> 26:40.509
why are you making it worse?

26:40.543 --> 26:41.810
Why not try to stop it?

26:41.844 --> 26:43.812
This is my defense?

26:43.846 --> 26:46.181
Actually, it is.

26:46.215 --> 26:51.686
♪

26:51.721 --> 26:57.392
♪

26:57.427 --> 26:59.828
1984 Garmeaux et Fournier.

26:59.862 --> 27:01.563
Correct.

27:01.597 --> 27:06.134
♪

27:06.169 --> 27:07.335
Hmm.

27:07.370 --> 27:09.237
2005 Domaine Greuze Bourgogne.

27:09.272 --> 27:16.011
♪

27:16.045 --> 27:22.751
♪

27:22.785 --> 27:25.253
This one isn't here.

27:25.288 --> 27:29.491
It's probably claiming to be that
bottle of 1997 Domaine Sagnier,

27:29.525 --> 27:31.359
which is a blend of pinot noir
and chardonnay,

27:31.394 --> 27:33.161
but it's actually a mix of...

27:33.196 --> 27:34.196
♪

27:34.230 --> 27:35.864
...Gamay...

27:35.898 --> 27:37.232
Pinot gris.

27:37.266 --> 27:40.869
♪

27:40.903 --> 27:42.504
That is correct.

27:42.538 --> 27:44.739
Here's the deal.

27:44.774 --> 27:46.575
You can continue with this case

27:46.609 --> 27:48.243
against a small player like Toby,

27:48.277 --> 27:49.945
who got into this forgery for noble,

27:49.979 --> 27:52.080
albeit misguided reasons,

27:52.115 --> 27:55.183
or you can retain the exclusive services

27:55.218 --> 27:57.786
of one of the most distinguished
palates in the world

27:57.820 --> 27:59.921
to help you in the detection
and prosecution

27:59.956 --> 28:02.557
of systematic, large-scale wine fraud...

28:02.592 --> 28:05.627
the kind of fraud that you
actually really care about.

28:05.661 --> 28:11.867
♪

28:11.901 --> 28:14.936
I really want to take you to France.

28:14.971 --> 28:17.973
♪

28:18.007 --> 28:20.742
[HORN HONKS]

28:25.081 --> 28:26.615
Go ahead.

28:27.817 --> 28:29.384
I believe that Congressman Stoller

28:29.418 --> 28:30.552
misappropriated campaign funds

28:30.586 --> 28:32.888
for the purposes of concealing
the affair he was having.

28:32.922 --> 28:34.923
File the case.

28:35.614 --> 28:38.326
But I don't believe I can prove it.

28:38.361 --> 28:39.961
I can walk you through my rationale.

28:39.996 --> 28:42.063
If there's no case, there's no case.

28:44.000 --> 28:46.601
Walking out of my office now
would be just fine.

28:46.636 --> 28:48.503
Thank you, Mr. Fox.

28:49.566 --> 28:51.673
Knox.

28:51.707 --> 28:52.841
Mr. Knox.

28:52.875 --> 28:59.981
♪

29:00.016 --> 29:02.951
Doesn't sound like the Nick Byrne I know.

29:02.985 --> 29:04.208
He used to be a judge.

29:04.242 --> 29:05.620
ROGER: People change.

29:05.655 --> 29:07.355
File an emergency Writ of Mandamus

29:07.390 --> 29:08.456
in the 2nd Circuit.

29:08.491 --> 29:10.926
That'll prevent Byrne from
giving the jury instruction.

29:10.960 --> 29:14.663
If he ignores that,
he's finished as a judge.

29:15.278 --> 29:18.934
We can file a superseding indictment
without any quantity of drugs.

29:18.969 --> 29:20.669
That would give the judge the flexibility

29:20.703 --> 29:22.437
to avoid the mandatory minimum.

29:22.471 --> 29:24.039
We don't do that.

29:24.073 --> 29:26.441
This is an exceptional circumstance.

29:28.077 --> 29:29.420
Why?

29:29.455 --> 29:31.646
This defendant has no priors
with jail time.

29:31.681 --> 29:32.948
That doesn't sound exceptional.

29:32.982 --> 29:34.983
That sounds like
what the law contemplates.

29:35.017 --> 29:36.618
Have you gone soft, Roger?

29:36.652 --> 29:38.353
File the Writ.

29:38.387 --> 29:45.126
♪

29:45.161 --> 29:46.628
File the Writ.

29:46.662 --> 29:52.200
♪

29:52.235 --> 29:53.902
Yes, sir.

29:53.936 --> 29:57.539
♪

29:57.573 --> 29:59.674
[CHUCKLES]

29:59.709 --> 30:01.676
Young and ruthless.

30:01.711 --> 30:03.378
Remember that?

30:03.412 --> 30:05.647
♪

30:14.929 --> 30:16.396
You shouldn't have done that.

30:16.431 --> 30:17.631
I was given an order.

30:17.665 --> 30:19.132
You can question an order.

30:19.167 --> 30:20.434
You have an ethical obligation

30:20.468 --> 30:21.968
to question an order
you don't believe in.

30:22.003 --> 30:23.904
[CHUCKLES]

30:23.938 --> 30:26.473
"You're prosecuting the case
because I told you to.

30:26.507 --> 30:27.874
I told you to prosecute the case

30:27.909 --> 30:29.476
because she broke the law."

30:29.510 --> 30:32.412
That's what you said last time
I questioned an order...

30:32.447 --> 30:33.613
of yours.

30:33.648 --> 30:35.882
Maybe I was wrong.

30:36.370 --> 30:38.504
I don't think you were.

30:40.001 --> 30:41.468
I filed the Writ.

30:47.888 --> 30:49.756
- No charges.
- Okay, then.

30:54.135 --> 30:55.802
I think I made the right decision.

30:55.837 --> 30:57.771
I'm worried my mom got into my head.

30:57.805 --> 31:00.006
Your mommy is in your head
and you're in my office.

31:00.041 --> 31:01.508
Everyone is suffering.

31:01.542 --> 31:03.095
Are you jealous?

31:03.130 --> 31:05.316
- Of what?
- Me.

31:05.350 --> 31:06.680
Why would I be jealous of you?

31:06.714 --> 31:08.500
'Cause I got the high-profile
case and you didn't.

31:08.534 --> 31:09.966
You mean the secret investigation

31:10.001 --> 31:12.118
that turned into nothing?
No. Not jealous.

31:12.153 --> 31:14.488
I'd understand if you were.

31:14.522 --> 31:16.623
What do you want from me? You
want me to drop everything

31:16.657 --> 31:18.391
to make you feel important? You
need to find somebody else

31:18.426 --> 31:20.494
to babysit your self-esteem.

31:20.528 --> 31:21.862
I don't want that job.

31:21.896 --> 31:23.296
You're so judgmental.

31:23.331 --> 31:24.664
Is that supposed to be an insult?

31:24.699 --> 31:26.600
- I can do better.
- Unlikely.

31:26.634 --> 31:27.968
You're cold.

31:28.002 --> 31:28.835
Ouchy.

31:28.870 --> 31:31.037
You're self-righteous. You're rigid.

31:31.072 --> 31:33.206
You're boring, predictable, bland,

31:33.241 --> 31:35.942
callow, shallow, pretentious,
sententious, whiny.

31:35.977 --> 31:38.211
These are insults.

31:38.246 --> 31:39.990
I want you to leave my office.

31:40.024 --> 31:41.548
- Would it work?
- Would what work?

31:41.582 --> 31:42.782
Us.

31:43.651 --> 31:45.118
Would we work?

31:46.627 --> 31:48.428
You asked me out for a drink
and I said no.

31:48.453 --> 31:52.690
Because I worried about
what would happen to us.

31:54.810 --> 31:56.344
Would it work?

32:04.377 --> 32:05.505
It was just a drink.

32:05.540 --> 32:09.119
I'm sorry if I gave you
the wrong impression.

32:12.113 --> 32:13.413
Nothing to be sorry about.

32:14.074 --> 32:15.441
Leonard?

32:17.043 --> 32:20.720
I scored it 7-6 in favor of "no charges."

32:20.755 --> 32:23.049
You did the right thing.

32:25.459 --> 32:27.294
Thanks for keeping score.

32:37.271 --> 32:38.705
[HORNS HONK]

32:38.739 --> 32:40.206
[ELEVATOR DINGS]

32:40.241 --> 32:42.742
Who delivers the Writ? Tina?

32:42.777 --> 32:45.579
I think so. I don't know.

32:45.613 --> 32:46.680
This is weird.

32:46.714 --> 32:47.714
Yes.

32:47.748 --> 32:49.716
Like, not in that way
where we don't know anything

32:49.750 --> 32:50.717
and we think everything is weird.

32:50.751 --> 32:52.719
This is actually weird.

32:52.753 --> 32:54.220
That way. Yes.

32:54.949 --> 32:56.616
When Byrne started 30 years ago,

32:56.641 --> 32:58.308
he probably walked in here every day.

32:58.333 --> 33:01.068
Feeling righteous,

33:01.093 --> 33:04.128
waking up, wanting to do the right thing,

33:04.153 --> 33:06.020
putting the bad guys in jail.

33:06.045 --> 33:08.680
I'm sure it's intoxicating, in theory.

33:08.810 --> 33:09.776
But it never ends.

33:09.904 --> 33:11.805
There's always another bad guy,

33:11.839 --> 33:13.974
and sometimes the bad guys
aren't that bad.

33:14.008 --> 33:16.876
It must break you a little every day.

33:16.911 --> 33:19.112
Not you... I don't mean you. Just...

33:19.146 --> 33:20.547
[SIGHS]

33:20.581 --> 33:22.538
...the idealism...

33:22.572 --> 33:23.783
the belief in the law

33:23.818 --> 33:25.885
and all that's right
and beautiful about it.

33:25.920 --> 33:27.426
♪

33:27.460 --> 33:29.623
Maybe it's hard to sustain.

33:29.657 --> 33:32.248
And then someone makes you a judge,

33:32.249 --> 33:35.285
and now... now you have the power

33:35.319 --> 33:36.619
because you decide.

33:36.654 --> 33:39.568
But you don't, not really.
Not all the time.

33:39.602 --> 33:40.857
At what point does some clerk

33:40.891 --> 33:42.826
find you in your chambers
rending your garments

33:42.860 --> 33:44.361
and carving "no hope" into your chest

33:44.395 --> 33:45.895
with a picture of your dog
looking over you?

33:45.930 --> 33:47.030
Dude.

33:47.064 --> 33:48.286
Yep. Sorry.

33:48.320 --> 33:50.500
[SIGHS] Just talking.

33:50.534 --> 34:00.577
♪

34:00.611 --> 34:03.813
I don't think Byrne's lost his idealism.

34:03.848 --> 34:05.515
I don't think
he'd be doing this if he did.

34:05.549 --> 34:07.517
I think that's what this is about.

34:07.551 --> 34:08.551
It's real.

34:08.585 --> 34:11.487
That righteous feeling
you wake up with ever day.

34:11.522 --> 34:13.089
I wake up with it.

34:13.123 --> 34:14.591
So do you.

34:14.625 --> 34:18.219
♪

34:18.254 --> 34:20.163
The Second Circuit granted the Writ.

34:21.899 --> 34:23.900
You can't issue those
instructions to the jury,

34:23.934 --> 34:25.101
which means...

34:25.136 --> 34:26.503
I know what it means.

34:30.040 --> 34:31.654
[SIGHS]

34:31.688 --> 34:33.610
It's time for me to step down.

34:33.643 --> 34:35.678
Then you don't know what that means.

34:37.148 --> 34:39.716
This all has to end somewhere.

34:40.650 --> 34:42.952
Julien Barley is dead.

34:42.987 --> 34:44.920
♪

34:44.955 --> 34:47.290
That is a fact.

34:47.324 --> 34:50.592
It is a cold, sad fact,

34:50.628 --> 34:52.762
but a fact nonetheless.

34:52.797 --> 34:55.231
I looked it up.

34:55.266 --> 34:57.867
You sentenced Julien Barley.

34:57.902 --> 35:00.870
A cold, sad fact.

35:01.457 --> 35:06.075
And nothing you're doing
is gonna bring him back.

35:06.110 --> 35:08.144
♪

35:08.179 --> 35:09.746
I don't normally lecture grown men

35:09.780 --> 35:11.548
because they're stupid
and they don't listen,

35:11.582 --> 35:13.383
but you need to hear this.

35:13.417 --> 35:16.152
You are rare.

35:17.098 --> 35:19.017
You are good.

35:19.657 --> 35:21.057
You're not the world's greatest judge,

35:21.091 --> 35:22.325
but you're better than most.

35:22.359 --> 35:24.394
You are fair.

35:24.428 --> 35:28.598
You are a black man.

35:28.632 --> 35:31.654
You keep hot sauce in your drawer.

35:32.703 --> 35:35.238
You do more staying on the bench

35:35.272 --> 35:37.507
than nailing yourself to this cross.

35:37.541 --> 35:43.146
♪

35:43.180 --> 35:44.781
That's it.

35:44.815 --> 35:45.849
I'm done.

35:45.883 --> 35:46.916
You're a grown man.

35:46.951 --> 35:48.588
The choice is yours.

35:53.657 --> 35:57.694
Just let me know if, uh...
I got to get my own.

35:57.728 --> 36:05.201
♪

36:08.284 --> 36:10.151
♪ Darling ♪

36:10.186 --> 36:13.655
♪ There's something that you don't know ♪

36:13.689 --> 36:16.558
♪ I said some things before ♪

36:16.592 --> 36:19.761
♪ Not so sure anymore ♪

36:19.795 --> 36:21.529
♪ I lose ♪

36:22.632 --> 36:28.403
♪ Give me something
that you can't choose ♪

36:28.437 --> 36:30.905
♪ We've been lost in this show ♪

36:30.940 --> 36:36.478
♪ We've mistaken the foe ♪

36:36.512 --> 36:41.850
♪ Give me something my heart can choose ♪

36:41.884 --> 36:45.654
♪ Guess you stole the unknown ♪

36:45.688 --> 36:47.822
♪ Brought me something I know ♪

36:47.857 --> 36:49.224
♪ Didn't you ♪

36:50.693 --> 36:55.664
♪ I'm in need of your love ♪

36:58.234 --> 37:03.438
♪ I'm in need of your love ♪

37:04.907 --> 37:09.811
♪ Is it the meaning of love ♪

37:11.881 --> 37:16.985
♪ I'm in need of your love ♪

37:19.055 --> 37:23.958
♪ I'm in need of your love ♪

37:25.828 --> 37:27.962
♪ Please me ♪

37:27.997 --> 37:30.899
♪ I don't need all your fears, there's ♪

37:30.933 --> 37:35.704
♪ Something you lose ♪

37:35.738 --> 37:37.605
♪ When we love ♪

37:39.942 --> 37:42.644
♪ Please me ♪

37:42.678 --> 37:45.547
♪ Heal my wound again ♪

37:47.183 --> 37:52.687
♪ Give me something
that you can't choose ♪

37:52.722 --> 37:55.890
♪ Maybe higher we'll grow ♪

37:55.925 --> 37:58.526
♪ We'll disappear in a blow ♪

37:58.561 --> 37:59.828
THERESA: All rise!

38:01.430 --> 38:04.399
The honorable
Judge Nicholas Byrne presiding.

38:04.433 --> 38:08.570
♪

38:08.604 --> 38:12.707
♪ I'm in need of your love ♪

38:12.742 --> 38:20.915
♪

38:20.950 --> 38:23.118
JUDGE BYRNE:
Will the defendant please rise?

38:23.152 --> 38:28.623
♪

38:28.657 --> 38:30.191
Mr. Puente, you have been found guilty

38:30.226 --> 38:31.760
of possession of a controlled substance

38:31.794 --> 38:33.528
with intent to distribute.

38:33.562 --> 38:35.263
This was a non-violent offense.

38:35.297 --> 38:36.531
You have been honest and forthright

38:36.565 --> 38:37.632
in this courtroom.

38:37.666 --> 38:39.067
You have shown remorse.

38:39.101 --> 38:40.935
As far as I can tell,

38:40.970 --> 38:42.570
you are a decent young man

38:42.605 --> 38:45.039
who found himself in a bad situation.

38:46.475 --> 38:48.309
I am not from New York,

38:49.078 --> 38:51.579
but I am a New Yorker.

38:52.372 --> 38:53.882
I cam here on a Greyhound bus

38:53.916 --> 38:56.985
from Gasden, Alabama in 1965.

38:57.019 --> 39:00.288
This city has changed
substantially since then.

39:00.322 --> 39:02.991
There are no cars in Times Square.

39:03.025 --> 39:05.460
Brooklyn is filled with high-rises.

39:05.494 --> 39:08.496
Black folks are a minority
in Harlem these days.

39:08.531 --> 39:11.999
Crime is at an all-time low in Manhattan.

39:13.969 --> 39:15.770
But no one ever seems

39:15.805 --> 39:19.073
to ask the question they should be asking

39:19.108 --> 39:22.885
in between their Broadway shows
and swanky dinners.

39:24.947 --> 39:26.981
"At what cost?"

39:27.016 --> 39:28.249
♪

39:28.284 --> 39:31.453
Here, from this bench,

39:31.487 --> 39:33.788
listening to cases just like yours,

39:33.823 --> 39:35.924
I see the cost.

39:35.958 --> 39:37.192
♪

39:37.226 --> 39:40.069
The cost looks me in the eye.

39:41.030 --> 39:44.132
The cost runs deep.

39:44.166 --> 39:46.034
♪

39:46.068 --> 39:47.936
It shatters lives,

39:47.970 --> 39:49.771
splinters families,

39:49.805 --> 39:51.172
destroys futures.

39:51.207 --> 39:53.174
It is unrepentant.

39:53.209 --> 39:55.677
♪

39:55.711 --> 39:59.514
This is rightly a bitter pill
to swallow, Mr. Puente...

39:59.548 --> 40:01.015
♪

40:01.050 --> 40:02.650
...but you are the cost.

40:02.685 --> 40:05.053
♪

40:05.087 --> 40:07.542
Julien Barley is the cost.

40:07.576 --> 40:13.027
♪

40:13.062 --> 40:15.363
[DOOR UNLOCKS]

40:15.397 --> 40:19.033
We are cannibalizing
a generation of New Yorkers...

40:19.068 --> 40:20.668
[DOOR CREAKS OPEN]

40:20.703 --> 40:22.637
...but this is happening
all over the country.

40:22.671 --> 40:25.740
Low-level, non-violent crimes

40:25.774 --> 40:31.012
that trigger disproportionate
mandatory minimum sentences.

40:31.871 --> 40:34.148
And I'm part of the problem.

40:34.183 --> 40:37.685
♪

40:37.720 --> 40:40.922
I have not spoken out
against these sentences.

40:41.464 --> 40:44.526
I've failed you, I failed Julien Barley,

40:44.560 --> 40:48.396
I've failed thousands of other
underrepresented people.

40:49.555 --> 40:53.167
I have not done my duty as a New Yorker,

40:53.202 --> 40:57.071
as a black American, as a father...

40:57.106 --> 41:00.074
to protect people who look like me,

41:00.109 --> 41:02.277
walk the same streets as I do,

41:02.311 --> 41:06.748
from laws that are not designed
to rehabilitate,

41:06.782 --> 41:08.950
but to destroy.

41:08.984 --> 41:10.718
♪

41:10.753 --> 41:13.788
My hands are reluctantly
and unwillingly tied

41:13.822 --> 41:15.223
in this situation.

41:15.257 --> 41:18.426
♪

41:18.460 --> 41:20.295
I have no choice

41:20.329 --> 41:22.730
but to sentence you, Mr. Puente,

41:22.765 --> 41:25.700
to 10 years in federal prison.

41:25.734 --> 41:28.036
♪

41:28.070 --> 41:29.404
I have no business

41:29.438 --> 41:32.874
asking anything of you, Mr. Puente,

41:32.908 --> 41:36.044
but I would ask you to take
a long look at your family

41:36.078 --> 41:38.713
on your way out of this courtroom.

41:39.939 --> 41:42.083
Lock that picture in your head

41:42.117 --> 41:44.052
and do not let go of it.

41:44.086 --> 41:46.154
♪

41:46.188 --> 41:47.455
Hold on to it.

41:47.489 --> 41:48.990
♪

41:49.024 --> 41:51.158
That is hope

41:51.760 --> 41:53.595
when there's no hope left.

41:53.629 --> 41:56.097
♪

41:56.131 --> 41:57.503
Please...

41:57.538 --> 42:01.469
do not let anyone
take that away from you.

42:01.503 --> 42:07.475
♪

42:07.509 --> 42:09.344
One last thing, Mr. Puente.

42:09.378 --> 42:11.079
♪

42:11.113 --> 42:12.981
I'm so very sorry.

